instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "Digital Twin development follows a multi‑layered MBSE lifecycle, beginning with high‑level requirements, progressing through functional architecture, logical architecture, and finally the product/technical implementation. At each layer the twin is represented in increasingly detailed models: requirements are captured in natural language and requirement tables; functional architecture is expressed in SysML Requirements diagrams and block definition diagrams; logical architecture uses SysML IBDs or ADLs such as ACME or AADL to describe component‑connector structure; the product/technical layer is modeled with simulation primitives in tools like MathWorks Simulink or MontiArc automata. Transition between layers is managed by traceability links and model transformation rules, ensuring that each abstraction level is consistently derived from the preceding one. Lifecycle governance is typically performed through a model management system that enforces version control, change request workflows, and compliance checks against the MBSE methodology."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin employs SysML v1.7 for architecture modeling, with component‑connector descriptions in SysML IBDs, block definition diagrams and requirement diagrams. For logical and functional architecture, ACME, AADL, and MontiArc are also used as ADL standards. Simulation behavior is implemented using MathWorks Simulink, which follows the Simulink modeling standard."
]
